> Easily is a relative term...ie relatively easily...they don't just slide
back,
> as there is a very tight seal around the outside of the caliper piston
that the
> piston has to move through, and you are pushing back a quantity of brake
fluid
> in the system at the same time...it needs to be relatively tight to keep
the
> fluid in without leaking out past the piston when brakes are applied...I
should
> be more learned with my wording after all these years....LOL
>
> My tool of choice here for returning the piston to the rest position is a
4-5"
> C-clamp, and one of the old pads laid across the top of the piston....with
the
> caliper unbolted from the spindle, and off rotor, I like to see a two
finger and
> thumb turn of the business end of the clamp (the t-handle end you screw
in)...if
> you have to muscle it, or use brute force to move the piston back in, the
> caliper should be rebuilt...and from experience, I NEVER replace one
> caliper...always the pair....otherwise you end up with a pull, and end up
> replacing the second one shortly afterwards anyways...and BTW...$70 ea
isn't a
> bad price for rebuilt if they're done well...try a 914 rear, or GTI rear,
and
> you'll know what sticker shock is...
>
> My rule on hub or drum is....if I'm doing just shoes as a maintenance
routine,
> and I know the star wheels and cylinders are working well, and not
leaking, then
> I just do the drum...cylinders, or removal/free-up of star adjusters gets
the
> hub out of the way...usually, on a new to me bus...it's the hub off the
first
> time, just to see how much play there is in the bearings, since they don't
get
> greased or serviced for years at a time if ever...
>
> Have fun...
>
> Den.
>
